Non-Rant Content: Having finally gotten wise after many years of making
vain attempts at pulling things, I've invested in some GOOD 2-jaw and
3-jaw pullers, as well as a GOOD tie-rod "popper-offer" tool.  St. Muir
and his #&!(-at-)(%^*! Propane torch and two-hammers method...  Wow!  My
goodness gracious and all the little creatures in the sea - I did ALL
the tie rods and the drag link on my '72 in about an hour-forty on one
boring Sunday afternoon - I had so much extra time left over, I had to
drive to the store and get another 6er.  St. Muir and his #&!(-at-)(%^*!
Propane torch and two-hammers method, indeed...  The GOOD 2-jaw puller
took care of the Pittman arm debacle when it was time for a steering box
replacement, plus some heat and some well placed BFTaps from the
BFHammer.  The GOOD 3-jaw puller can do stuff like remove the crank gear
stack on a T4 crank, and (saints-be-praised) the impeller hub itself off
of the crank, too.  Tension it down a little on the hub, a little heat,
some well placed LFTaps from the LFHammer, some Kroil, and
"sproingggkkkk!" - you're done!    The cheap multipurpose harmonic
balancer puller tool pretty much stripped it's center bolt the first
time I used it, the much more expensive one from Lisle (I think) - I
keep forgetting where it is...  But the GOOD 3-jaw puller?  I know where
that thing lives!

And when it all goes back together?  The crank taper snout / impeller
hub interface gets a reasonable smearing of anti-seize...  for the next
poor sap :-)  Now if you'll excuse me, there's a Class 5 off-road car
down in Mexicali I gotta go perform the "laying-on of hands" to it's 44
IDFs - race is tomorrow!

